<STEP id="78" group="2" skill="2">
      <NAME language="de">Meta Suffix</NAME>
      <NAME language="uk">Meta Suffix</NAME>
      <HELP language="de">
	    Von: [[a href="http://www.informatik.uni-hamburg.de/Frauen/Admina/Beitraege/www_server/Config1.htm" target="_blank"]]http://www.informatik.uni-hamburg.de/Frauen/Admina/Beitraege/www_server/Config1.htm[[/a]][[br]][[br]]
	    
	    MetaSuffix gibt das Dateinamensuffix f&uuml;r die Datei an, die die Metainformationen enth&auml;lt (zus&auml;tzliche HTTP-Header), 
	    die im Verzeichnis MetaDir directory abgelegt sein sollten.
	    
      </HELP>
      <HELP language="uk">
	    From: http.conf[[br]][[br]]

	    MetaSuffix: specifies the file name suffix for the file containing the
	    meta information.

      </HELP>
      <TYPE kind="standard" input="textline" number="1" default=".meta" key="MetaSuffix" notinstart="^\s*&lt;Vir.+?&gt;" notinstop="^\s*&lt;/Vir.+?&gt;"></TYPE>	
</STEP>

<STEP id="80" group="3" skill="2">
      <NAME language="de">Name Virtual Host</NAME>
      <NAME language="uk">Name Virtual Host</NAME>
      <HELP language="de">
	    Von: [[a href="http://www.informatik.uni-hamburg.de/Frauen/Admina/Beitraege/www_server/Config1.htm" target="_blank"]]http://www.informatik.uni-hamburg.de/Frauen/Admina/Beitraege/www_server/Config1.htm[[/a]][[br]][[br]]
	    
	    Wenn Sie namensbasierte virtuelle Hosts einrichten, m&uuml;ssen Sie die Anweisung NameVirtualHost f&uuml;r die IP-Adresse 
	    verwenden (und die Portnummer, falls erforderlich). Die Konfiguration von namensbasierten virtuellen 
	    Hosts wird verwendet, wenn Sie verschiedene virtuelle Hosts f&uuml;r verschiedene Dom&auml;nen einrichten m&ouml;chten, 
	    aber nicht gen&uuml;gend verschiedene IP-Adressen f&uuml;r die verschiedenen Dom&auml;nennamen haben (oder 
	    verwenden m&ouml;chten), f&uuml;r die Ihr Web-Server Dokumente bereitstellt.
	    [[br]][[br]]
	    [[b]]Bitte beachten[[/b]]
 	    [[br]][[br]]
	    Namensbasierte virtuelle Hosts k&ouml;nnen nicht gemeinsam mit dem Secure Server verwendet werden. 
	    Alle eingerichteten namensbasierten virtuelle Hosts funktionieren nur f&uuml;r unverschl&uuml;sselte 
	    HTTP-Verbindungen, nicht f&uuml;r SSL-Verbindungen.
	    [[br]][[br]]
	    Namensbasierte virtuelle Hosts k&ouml;nnen nicht zusammen mit dem Secure Server verwendet werden, weil 
	    der SSL-Handshake (der Zeitpunkt, wenn der Browser das Authentifizierungszertifikat des Secure 
	    Web-Servers annimmt) vor der HTTP-Anforderung stattfindet, die den richtigen namensbasierten 
	    virtuellen Host identifiziert. Anders ausgedr&uuml;ckt, die Authentifizierung findet statt, bevor die 
	    Identifikation der verschiedenen namensbasierten virtuellen Host erfolgt. Virtuelle Hosts 
	    m&uuml;ssen IP-Adressen-basiert sein, um sie gemeinsam mit dem Secure Server verwenden zu k&ouml;nnen.
	    [[br]][[br]]
	    Wenn Sie namensbasierte virtuelle Hosts verwenden, sind f&uuml;r die Konfigurationsanweisung 
	    NameVirtualHost die Kommentare zu entfernen, und nach NameVirtualHost ist die richtige IP-Adresse 
	    f&uuml;r Ihren Server anzugeben. Anschlie&szlig;end sind mit VirtualHost-Tags weitere Informationen zu den 
	    verschiedenen Dom&auml;nen hinzuzuf&uuml;gen, die ServerName f&uuml;r jeden virtuellen Host sowie weitere 
	    Konfigurationsanweisungen einschlie&szlig;en, die nur f&uuml;r diesen virtuellen Host gelten. 	    
      </HELP>
      <HELP language="uk">
	    From: [[a href="http://httpd.apache.org/docs/mod/core.html#ifmodule" target="_blank"]]http://httpd.apache.org/docs/mod/core.html#ifmodule[[/a]]
	    [[br]][[br]]
	    The NameVirtualHost directive is a required directive if you want to configure name-based virtual hosts.
	    [[br]][[br]]
	    Although addr can be hostname it is recommended that you always use an IP address or wildcard, e.g.
	    [[br]][[br]]
	    NameVirtualHost 111.22.33.44 
	    [[br]][[br]]
	    With the NameVirtualHost directive you specify the IP address on which the server will receive requests 
	    for the name-based virtual hosts. This will usually be the address to which your name-based virtual host 
	    names resolve. In cases where a firewall or other proxy receives the requests and forwards them on a 
	    different IP address to the server, you must specify the IP address of the physical interface on the 
	    machine which will be servicing the requests. If you have multiple name-based hosts on multiple addresses, 
	    repeat the directive for each address.
	    [[br]][[br]]
	    Note: the "main server" and any _default_ servers will never be served for a request to a NameVirtualHost 
	    IP Address (unless for some reason you specify NameVirtualHost but then don't define any VirtualHosts 
	    for that address).
	    [[br]][[br]]
	    Optionally you can specify a port number on which the name-based virtual hosts should be used, e.g.
	    [[br]][[br]]
	    NameVirtualHost 111.22.33.44:8080 
	    [[br]][[br]]
	    In Apache 1.3.13 and greater you can specify a * for the addr. This creates a wildcard 
	    NameVirtualHost which will match connections to any address that isn't configured with a more specific 
	    NameVirtualHost directive or &lt;VirtualHost&gt; section. This is useful if you want only name-based 
	    virtual hosts and you don't want to hard-code the server's IP address into the configuration file.
	    [[br]][[br]]
	    See also: Apache Virtual Host documentation
      </HELP>
      <TYPE kind="standard" input="textline" number="0" default="*" key="NameVirtualHost" notinstart="^\s*&lt;Vir.+?&gt;" notinstop="^\s*&lt;/Vir.+?&gt;"></TYPE>	
</STEP>

<STEP id="82" group="3" skill="2">
      <NAME language="de">Virtual Host</NAME>
      <NAME language="uk">Virtual Host</NAME>
      <HELP language="de">
	    Von: [[a href="http://www.tu-chemnitz.de/linux/Dokumentation/redhat-docs/RH-DOCS/de/rhl-rg-de-7.2/s1-apache-config.html" target="_blank"]]http://www.tu-chemnitz.de/linux/Dokumentation/redhat-docs/RH-DOCS/de/rhl-rg-de-7.2/s1-apache-config.html[[/a]][[br]][[br]]

	    &lt;VirtualHost&gt;- und &lt;/VirtualHost&gt;-Tags umschlie&szlig;en alle Konfigurationsanweisungen, die f&uuml;r einen 
	    virtuellen Host gelten. Die meisten Konfigurationsanweisungen k&ouml;nnen innerhalb von VirtualHost-Tags 
	    verwendet werden und gelten dann f&uuml;r diesen virtuellen Host.
	    [[br]][[br]]
	    Eine Reihe von auskommentierten VirtualHost-Tags umschlie&szlig;en einige Beispielkonfigurationsanweisungen 
	    und Platzhalter f&uuml;r die Informationen, die f&uuml;r die Einrichtung eines virtuellen Hosts ben&ouml;tigt 
	    w&uuml;rden. Weitere Informationen &uuml;ber virtuelle Hosts finden Sie in Abschnitt namens Virtuelle Hosts 
	    verwenden.       
      </HELP>
      <HELP language="uk">
	    From: [[a href="http://httpd.apache.org/docs/mod/core.html#ifmodule" target="_blank"]]http://httpd.apache.org/docs/mod/core.html#ifmodule[[/a]]
	    [[br]][[br]]
	    &lt;VirtualHost&gt; and &lt;/VirtualHost&gt; are used to enclose a group of directives which will apply 
	    only to a particular virtual host. Any directive which is allowed in a virtual host context may be 
	    used. When the server receives a request for a document on a particular virtual host, it uses the 
	    configuration directives enclosed in the &lt;VirtualHost&gt; section. Addr can be
	    [[br]][[br]]
	    * The IP address of the virtual host[[br]]
    	    * A fully qualified domain name for the IP address of the virtual host.[[br]][[br]]

	    Example:[[br]]

	    &lt;VirtualHost 10.1.2.3&gt;[[br]]
	    ServerAdmin webmaster@host.foo.com[[br]]
	    DocumentRoot /www/docs/host.foo.com[[br]]
	    ServerName host.foo.com[[br]]
	    ErrorLog logs/host.foo.com-error_log[[br]]
	    TransferLog logs/host.foo.com-access_log[[br]]
	    &lt;/VirtualHost&gt; 
  	    [[br]][[br]]
	    Each VirtualHost must correspond to a different IP address, different port number or a different host 
	    name for the server, in the former case the server machine must be configured to accept IP packets 
	    for multiple addresses. (If the machine does not have multiple network interfaces, then this can 
	    be accomplished with the ifconfig alias command (if your OS supports it), or with kernel patches 
	    like VIF (for SunOS(TM) 4.1.x)).
	    [[br]][[br]]
	    You can specify more than one IP address. This is useful if a machine responds to the same name on 
	    two different interfaces. For example, if you have a VirtualHost that is available to hosts on 
	    an internal (intranet) as well as external (internet) network. Example:
	    [[br]][[br]]
	    &lt;VirtualHost 192.168.1.2 204.255.176.199&gt;[[br]]
    	    DocumentRoot /www/docs/host.foo.com[[br]]
    	    ServerName host.foo.com[[br]]
    	    ServerAlias host[[br]]
    	    &lt;/VirtualHost&gt; 	
	    [[br]][[br]]
	    The special name _default_ can be specified in which case this virtual host will match any IP address 
	    that is not explicitly listed in another virtual host. In the absence of any _default_ virtual host 
	    the "main" server config, consisting of all those definitions outside any VirtualHost section, 
	    is used when no match occurs.
	    [[br]][[br]]
	    You can specify a :port to change the port that is matched. If unspecified then it defaults to 
	    the same port as the most recent Port statement of the main server. You may also specify :* 
	    to match all ports on that address. (This is recommended when used with _default_.)
	    [[br]][[br]]
	    SECURITY: See the security tips document for details on why your security could be compromised 
	    if the directory where logfiles are stored is writable by anyone other than the user that starts 
	    the server.
	    [[br]][[br]]
	    NOTE: The use of &lt;VirtualHost&gt; does not affect what addresses Apache listens on. You may 
	    need to ensure that Apache is listening on the correct addresses using either BindAddress or Listen.
      </HELP>
      <TYPE kind="user" input="subset" number="0" subsetid="1">
      	<START>^\s*&lt;VirtualHost.*?&gt;</START>
      	<STOP>&lt;/VirtualHost&gt;</STOP>
      </TYPE>	
</STEP>

